<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="137" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,151,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Remarks</emphasis>
. This new species resembles 
<emphasis box="[636,757,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. narusei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" box="[764,991,151,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng, 
<number box="[932,991,152,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, from 
<collectingCountry box="[1062,1126,152,175]" name="Japan" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Japan</collectingCountry>
in having short P 
<number box="[1322,1335,152,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
–P 
<number box="[1366,1380,152,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="4.0">4</number>
with the merus possessing a barely indiscernible median groove on the outer surface. The two species, however, are easily separated. The surfaces of the third maxilliped of 
<emphasis box="[782,904,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. narusei</emphasis>
is relatively less granular (
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng 
<number box="[1372,1432,224,248]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: fig. 
<number box="[199,228,260,284]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="40.0">40</number>
D
</bibRefCitation>
) than in 
<taxonomicName box="[356,472,261,284]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Mariaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[356,472,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[482,548,260,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[482,548,260,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[566,637,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 6. A – F" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1246,1268]" captionTargetBox="[163,1419,187,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1435,175,1233]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. A – F, Hexapinus latipes (De Haan, 1835), male (20.9 × 12.5 mm) (SMF ZMG 160 a), Ambon, Indonesia; G, H, Mariaplax aspera n. sp., holotype female (6.4 × 4.4 mm) (MZB), Lombok, Indonesia. A, ventral view of left G 1; B, dorsal view of left G 1; C, ventral view of distal part of left G 1; D, dorsal view of distal part of left G 1 (setae not drawn); E, left G 2 (ventral view); F, distal half of left G 2 (dorsal view); G, left third maxilliped; H, female abdomen. Scales: A, B, E, G, H = 1.0 mm; C, D, F = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241821/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number box="[622,637,260,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
H); and the telson of the female is equal in length to somite 
<number box="[1345,1359,260,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="6.0">6</number>
of the abdomen (
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" box="[269,605,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng 
<number box="[437,497,296,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: fig. 
<number box="[554,583,296,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="40.0">40</number>
H
</bibRefCitation>
) (telson slightly shorter than somite 
<quantity box="[1021,1065,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" unit="in" value="6.0">6 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[1073,1187,297,320]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Mariaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1073,1187,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1195,1259,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1195,1259,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1274,1352,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 6. A – F" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1246,1268]" captionTargetBox="[163,1419,187,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1435,175,1233]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. A – F, Hexapinus latipes (De Haan, 1835), male (20.9 × 12.5 mm) (SMF ZMG 160 a), Ambon, Indonesia; G, H, Mariaplax aspera n. sp., holotype female (6.4 × 4.4 mm) (MZB), Lombok, Indonesia. A, ventral view of left G 1; B, dorsal view of left G 1; C, ventral view of distal part of left G 1; D, dorsal view of distal part of left G 1 (setae not drawn); E, left G 2 (ventral view); F, distal half of left G 2 (dorsal view); G, left third maxilliped; H, female abdomen. Scales: A, B, E, G, H = 1.0 mm; C, D, F = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241821/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
Figs. 
<number box="[1338,1352,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
H, 
<number box="[1387,1402,296,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="7.0">7</number>
C). The carapace of 
<emphasis box="[338,460,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. narusei</emphasis>
is also proportionately broader (
<number box="[829,865,332,356]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="1.7">1.7</number>
times as broad as long versus 
<number box="[1210,1245,332,357]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="1.5">1.5</number>
as broad as long in 
<taxonomicName box="[182,297,369,392]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Mariaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[182,297,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[307,371,367,392]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[307,371,367,392]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[388,466,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[189,1396,193,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[189,1397,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Mariaplax aspera n. sp., holotype female (6.4 × 4.4 mm) (MZB), Lombok, Indonesia. A, overall habitus; B, frontal view of cephalothorax and chelae; C, thoracic sternum and abdomen; D, sternoabdominal cavity and vulvae (v)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241822/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
Figs. 
<number box="[452,466,368,392]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A), however, this difference should be regarded with caution as the specimens of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. narusei</emphasis>
examined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" box="[396,636,404,429]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng (
<number box="[570,629,404,428]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
are larger than the present species (
<number box="[1044,1123,404,429]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="10.8" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="9.6">9.6–12</number>
× 
<quantity box="[1154,1290,404,429]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.449999999999999" metricValueMax="7.1" metricValueMin="5.8" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" unit="mm" value="6.449999999999999" valueMax="7.1" valueMin="5.8">5.8–7.1 mm</quantity>
versus 
<number box="[1377,1412,404,429]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="6.4">6.4</number>
× 
<quantity box="[151,237,440,464]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" unit="mm" value="4.4">4.4 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName box="[272,385,441,464]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Mariaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis box="[272,385,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and carapace proportion does vary with the size of the specimen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
The mesial margin of the ischium of the third maxilliped is rounded, resembling that of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1309,1428,477,500]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1309,1428,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Hexapinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the ischium is proportionately broader in 
<taxonomicName box="[654,774,512,535]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[654,774,512,535]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Hexapinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with the distomesial margin usually more expanded. In 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Mariaplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">M. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[236,301,548,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[236,301,548,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, however, the ischium of the third maxilliped is as broad as the merus with the mesial margin not distinctly expanded. This is one of the key diagnostic characters for 
<emphasis box="[914,1032,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Mariaplax</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" box="[1039,1264,583,608]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng, 
<number box="[1208,1264,584,608]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng 
<number box="[151,212,620,644]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
: 
<number box="[222,269,620,644]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="424.0">424</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Fourteen 
<emphasis box="[394,512,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Mariaplax</emphasis>
species are currently known from the Indo-West Pacific region, though none have been previously reported from Lombok and neighbouring islands. Lombok has two hexapodid species: 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">Hexapinus simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Rahayu &amp; Ng 2014" authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[291,627,692,717]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[291,380,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="137">H. latus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rahayu" box="[394,619,692,717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" refString="Rahayu, D. L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2014) New genera and new species of Hexapodidae (Crustacea, Brachyura) from the Indo-West Pacific and east Atlantic. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 62, 396 - 483." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rahayu &amp; Ng 
<number box="[558,619,692,716]" pageId="12" pageNumber="137" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
